    <annotation>
      <linklist>
        <link xlink:href="https://www-ncbi-nlm-nih-gov.insb.bib.cnrs.fr/pubmed/26235892"/>
        <link xlink:href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/26235892"/>
      </linklist>
      <comment>Based on public and novel data from molecular genetic experiments (qPCR, western blot, EMSA), along with genome-wide assays (RNA-seq, ChIP-seq), this logical model recapitulates cytokine-induced differentiation of common progenitors myeloid-lymphoid progenitors, the effect of various reported gene knock-downs, as well as reprogramming of pre-B cells into macrophages induced by ectopic expression of CEBPa and CEBPb factors (van Oevelen et al (20015) Stem Cell Report). 

This model explicitly distinguishes between genes, proteins, and activated proteins for several key network players, in order to enable the reproduction of specific temporal behaviour.

A simple version of this network can be obtained by applying one of the model reductions associated with this model (e.g. reduce_proteins, to obtain the regulatory graph of Figure 3 in Collombet et al, PNAS, in press).

For some factors, several nodes are considered to represent the gene (factor_gene), the protein (factor) and the active form of the protein (factor_active). This was introduced to account for post-translational regulation (cytokine receptors activation by their ligand, and protein-protein interaction, etc). Otherwise, nodes represent both the gene and the corresponding protein. 

The reduction "Reduce_proteins" reduce the multi-level nodes (gene-protein-active protein) and results in only one node for each factor, reducing the complexity of stable states analysis or simulations.

Using this reduction, the model exhibits four stables states (plus one stable state with all variables at 0, independently of the state of the inputs cytokines Il7 and Csf1). These four states correspond to CLP, GMP, B cells and Macrophages as defined in the “Run simulation” panel. CLP and GMP states are stable only in the absence of Il7 or Cs1 (respectively), as these cytokines enable differentiation into B cells and macrophages, respectively.

Normal differentiation can be simulated from multipotent progenitors, as defined in the simulation panel (MP). In the absence of inputs, the MP can lead to GMP or CLP. In the presence of inputs, they can tends toward B cell or macrophage (see simulation presets "Dif: ....").

Reprogramming of B cells into macrophages can be simulated with constant or transient ectopic expression of Cebpa in B cells (see "Bcell-Repro" simulation presets, which include Cebpa expression combined with various perturbations). 

Reverse reprogramming from macrophages to B cells can be simulated by ectopic expression of combinations of B cell factors in macrophages (see "Mac-Repro" presets).</comment>
    </annotation>
  </graph>
</gxl>
